  m_Name: Level_13_San Andres
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  levelNumber: 13
  levelName: "San Andr\xE9s"
  location: La Libertad, El Salvador
  levelDescription: "From volcanic ash rose a valley capital, where pyramids guarded
    trade, ceremony, and time itself.\n\nThe Valley Capital of the Maya, located
    in the Zapotit\xE1n Valley of central El Salvador, was first settled around 900
    BC. After being abandoned due to the massive Ilopango volcanic eruption (c. 250
    AD), it was reoccupied in the 5th century and rose to prominence during the Late
    Classic period (600\u2013900 AD).\r\n\r\nAt its height, San Andr\xE9s served
    as a regional capital, controlling nearby settlements and acting as a hub for
    political and ceremonial life. The site includes an acropolis with pyramids,
    plazas, and more than 60 identified mounds. Farmers in the surrounding valley
    grew staples like corn, beans, and squash, supporting the city\u2019s population.\r\n\r\nArchaeologists
    have also uncovered evidence of trade links with Cop\xE1n in Honduras and the
    Guatemalan highlands, showing San Andr\xE9s was part of a wider Maya network.
    Later, during colonial times, the area became an indigo plantation, and remnants
    of this history can still be seen alongside the ancient ruins.\r\n\r\nToday,
    San Andr\xE9s is preserved as an archaeological park, where visitors can explore
    its pyramids, plazas, and museum exhibits that connect the Maya past with El
    Salvador\u2019s broader heritage"
  siteImage: {fileID: 21300000, guid: 4dfadb4d94e2fde4e927910b54a830d5, type: 3}
